bug.short_desc: Allow user pass emitter specific parameters through url

long_desc.thetext:
Current default BIRT viewer implementation only parses some known parameters from url. Normally, these parameters include format, locale, rtl setting, etc. But for some extended emitter which have some specific rendering settings, they may want to control this on the fly during runtime.
For instance, an XLS emitter may want to know if ouput as a single sheet before rendering. A user may just append a parameter in URL to tell this, like "&__single_page=true". The concrete emitter will be responsible to read and interprete these parameters. It's better if viewer can just pass through these specific values to emitter and hence leads to more flexibilities.

Fixed > 20061127.
Default viewer implementation now will pass parameters start with "__" from request into rendering options, emitter could read them through IEmitterSerivices and do proper their own logic.
Note concrete emitter implementation may need change to support read and recognize these options.

bug.short_desc: [api] Need IHostShell#waitFor(), IHostShell#writeToShellAndWait()

long_desc.thetext: Dave's - can you comment on this idea?

We have something like that in RemoteCommandShellOperation, which is a wrapper to the basic shell stuff. I works via an echo tag as suggested here. I wonder whether this functionality should be left at a layer above services or whether we should do it at the service layer. I suppose doing it at the service layer would allow for protocol-specific optimizations. What do you think?

That's very interesting! In fact, RemoteCommandShellOperation seems to be doing what we need, though it appears to be more complex than required -- a simple "writeToShellAndWait()" appears to be easier to use.
Unfortunately, currently there is no sample usage of RemoteCommandShellOperation anywhere in openRSE. I think that when the ssh processes contribution is accepted by EMO Legal and checked in, we should re-write it to use RemoteCommandShellOperation.
Having a sample usage of this will allow us to better understand what it does and decide whether it should eventually be at service or subsystem layer.

One disadvantage of RemoteCommandShellOperation in terms of performance, seems to be that it goes all way through the (global) resource change mechanism.
I guess that in many cases, only a single consumer of an IHostShell will be interested in it, so some "peer to peer" communications between the shell and the consumer would be more effective.
We also have a similar utility called SimpleCommandOperation. This wrapper is nice in that it is fairly simple, however it doesn't do the command tagging stuff.

bug.short_desc: opposite property of org.osgi.framework.bootdelegation

long_desc.thetext: need a property to do the opposite of org.osgi.framework.bootdelegation instead of having a long list of what is allowed from the parent classloader if user just want to disable something from the parent classloader.

This is a "standard" property defined in the OSGi spec. We could of course implement another property or some sort of special case here but we try really hard not to introduce "containerisms". Perhaps you should direct this as input to the OSGi spec process at http://www2.osgi.org/bugzilla/
*** Bug 165034 has been marked as a duplicate of this bug. ***

also see bug 145585. Now that boot delegation is no longer * the original usecase is gone and I'm less sure that this is the best way to expose these resources.
Framework extension bundles {3.15 of the spec} might be another approach to consider.

I'd suggest you make the request to OSGi at http://www2.osgi.org/bugzilla/
But first I encourage you to look at other options because I do not think a new property will be easy to push into the spec. We had a hard enough time pushing for bootdelegation ;-)
Like Simon says in comment 3, in Equinox we no longer default to bootdelegation *. In fact we do not define it at all, which means only java.* packages are delegated to boot automatically (see http://wiki.eclipse.org/index.php/Equinox_Boot_Delegation) for more information. Another approach is for you to define framework fragments that export the additional packages you want to expose from the VM (that are not already included in the standard EE profile for the VM specification). This way your bundles can use Import-Package for the packages just like any other package in the system.

bug.short_desc: BIRT Test reports are not generated on Linux

long_desc.thetext:
Can not generate TPTP test reports on Linux.
The problem is that the extension point uses a file separator that is specific to the windows operating system. That is it uses '\' character instead of the '/' character.
The fix is isolated in the org.eclipse.tptp.test.report.birt/plugin.xml file. There is no code changes. Only two entries in the plugin.xml file needs to be modified.
There is no work around for this problem.

Created an attachment (id=54079) Patch that fixes this problem.
This patch has been tested on linux. Will conduct window testing to verify patch.

1) Explain why you believe this is a stop-ship defect. How does the defect manifest itself, and how will users of TPTP / consuming products be affected if the defect is not fixed?
BIRT test reports will not generate on Linux. As a result users can not generate Test pass or tabular reports on Linux machines.
2) Is there a work-around? If so, why do you believe the work-around is insufficient?
There is no work-around.
3) Is this a regression or API breakage? Explain.
This is a regression since 4.2, which did not show this problem.
4) Does this require new API?
No.
5) Who performed the code review?
Sheldon Lee-Loy
6) Is there a test case attached to the bugzilla record?
No, but regressions that the fix might cause are covered by running BIRT Test suites on Linux (Platform.Reporting_BIRT.testsuite).
7) What is the risk associated with this fix?
The fix only touches the plugin.xml file stored in org.eclipse.tptp.test.report.birt. The problem is that the extension point uses a file separator that is specific to the windows operating system. That is it uses '\' character instead of the '/' character.
Before the fix: <property name="CONTEXT_TEMPLATE_FILE" value="templates\TabularReport.rptdesign"/> <property name="CONTEXT_CHILD_TEMPLATEFILE" value="templates\TabularSubReport.rptdesign"/> <property name="CONTEXT_TEMPLATE_FILE" value="templates\TestExecution.rptdesign"/>
After the fix: <property name="CONTEXT_TEMPLATE_FILE" value="templates/TabularReport.rptdesign"/> <property name="CONTEXT_CHILD_TEMPLATEFILE" value="templates/TabularSubReport.rptdesign"/> <property name="CONTEXT_TEMPLATE_FILE" value="templates/TestExecution.rptdesign"/>
8) Is this fix related to any standards that TPTP adheres to? If so, who has validated that the fix continues to adhere to the standard?
No.
Verified the patch works on Windows.
Will be packaged with the fix from https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=164637.
File affected: /cvsroot/tptp/test/org.eclipse.tptp.test.report.birt/plugin.xml
